body:
B. Provincial news:

1. 16:31 Video report about casualties of the Chaharshanbeh&#160;Suri bonfire festival celebrated on 12 March.&#160;Four teenagers have been hospitalised in Ezhiyeh.&#160;

2. 16:37 Video report about programmes and ceremonies carried out in the province on the occasion of Martyrs Day. Provincial authorities, military personnel and people have visited martyrs' cemeteries across the province.

3. 16:40 A "martyrs" commemoration ceremony has been held in Kashan.&#160; &#160;

4. 16:43 Video report on the meeting of the Air Pollution Control Workgroup of the province in Isfahan.&#160;

5. 16:46 The Supreme Leader's&#160;representative in the province,&#160;Ayatollah Tabatabainejad, has met with the head of Islamic Propagation Coordination Council of the province on the occasion of the start of fasting month of Ramadan.

C. Provincial news in brief:

1. 16:47 Charitable essential products have been distributed among 800 needy families in Dorcheh.&#160;

2. 16:47 A Quran reciting ceremony has been held in Mahabad City of Ardestan County.&#160;

3. 16:47 A "martyrs" commemoration ceremony has been held in Isfahan.&#160; &#160;

4. 16:47 Repot on a funeral procession held for the father of Iran-Iraq war "martyred" Rashidi brothers in Falavarjan.

5. 16:47 Trees have been planted in different regions of the province on the occasion of Martyrs Day.

6. 16:48 Nowruz (Iranian New Year)&#160;Trips Service HQ of Khur-Biabanak has staged drills ahead of the start of trips.

7. 16:48 Report on the meeting of the Flour and Bread HQ of Ardestan County.

8. 16:48 A students' handicrafts exhibition has been staged in Meymeh.

D. More provincial news:

1. 16:49 A festival has been held in a school in Isfahan.&#160;

2. 16:50 A show of classic cars has been held in Shahinshahr.&#160;

E. 16:52 Sport.

F. 16:54 Weather, calendar and prayer times.

16:55 End of bulletin.

Source: Vision of the Islamic Republic of Iran Isfahan Provincial TV, Esfahan, in Persian 1630 GMT 12 Mar 24

B. Provincial news:

1. 19:31 According to the Information Supply Committee of the Central Election HQ, 43,12% of population of the province participated in the parliamentary and Assembly of Experts elections on 1 March.

2. 19:32 Thirty-five people have been injured in the province from petards and explosives during the Chaharshanbeh&#160;Suri bonfire festival celebrated on 12 March.

3. 19:33 Video report on Quran-reciting ceremonies in the province on the occasion of the fasting month of Ramadan.&#160; &#160;

4. 19:35 Video report on tightening market supervision ahead of the start of Nowruz (Iranian New Year) holidays.

5. 19:36 Samanu - a sweet paste made from germinated wheat (young wheatgrass) and wheat flour &#8211; whoch is one of elements of Haft Sin (Seven S) traditional table of Nowruz, has been registered in the list of intangible national heritage of Iran. Video report.

6. 19:38 Video report on the meeting of executive and Judiciary officials of the province aimed at discussing implementation of the Clean Air Law in the province.&#160;

C. 19:39 Weather.

D. Other news:

1. 19:40 Video report about programmes and ceremonies carried out in the province on the occasion of Martyrs Day.&#160;

2. 19:42 The deputy governor-general for economic affairs is interviewed over the phone about decisions taken during the meeting of the province's HQ for removing obstacles in the manufacturing field.

3. 19:45 "Arabic joke" TV series will be aired on the provincial TV during Ramadan.&#160;

E. Provincial news in brief:

1. 19:48 Head of the Payam-e Nur University of the province has met with representatives of student organisations in Ahvaz.

2. 19:49 A murderer who was sentenced to death has been pardoned by the family of victim in Behbahan.

3. 19:49 A 2.8 magnitude earthquake hit Sardasht City of Dezful.&#160;

4. 19:49 Charitable dowries have been allocated to 91 needy couples in Masjed Soleiman.

F. More provincial news:

1. 19:50 Video report on the start of mulberry trees planting activities in Jannat Makan City of Gotvand County.&#160;

2. 19:51 Tuesday rubric called "Frontier line" dedicated to discussing the problems of the province in social and other fields.&#160;

G. 19:54 Sport.&#160;

H. 19:57 Calendar and prayer times.

19:58 End of bulletin.

Source: Vision of the Islamic Republic of Iran Khuzestan Provincial TV, Ahvaz, in Persian 1930 GMT 12 Mar 24

Rehman opened the show by saying that "only a day after taking the oath of his office Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif visited the calamity-hit people of Gwadar". He mentioned that Gwadar and surrounding areas in South Balochistan have been badly affected by recent heavy rains. He reported that the prime minister announced "financial support packages" for the affected people in the area.&#160;

Rehman mentioned that earlier in his speech in the National Assembly, the prime minister had emphasised the need for "tough measures" and "unpopular decisions" to turn around the economy of Pakistan. He spoke to Khaqan Najeeb, an expert on economic affairs and asked him to comment on the prime minister's visit to Gwadar. Najeeb said the visit was a good step by the new government because Gwadar is important in connection with the CPEC [China-Pakistan Economic Corridor]. He said Gwadar was being built as a new city so it should be ensured that it has a "world-class" drainage and sanitation system and that in the future such problems do not occur. He also noted that Gwadar port is important for the future trade by Pakistan with regional countries including China.

Abdullah Mohmand, an analyst, said a day earlier the prime minister in his speech in the National Assembly had emphasised that he would try to address the "issues and grievances of the people of Balochistan" and today he visited Balochistan. He noted that by visiting the calamity-stricken people of Balochistan the prime minister "assured the people there that the government would provide them all kind of support". He mentioned that development works in the area would only be possible when the people there "trust the government and the state".&#160;

Speaking about the challenges faced by the new government Mohmand said the "biggest challenge" was political instability because without political stability neither the economy could be improved nor the issues of climate change could be addressed. He said: "The economy is in turmoil at the moment" and foreign investment would not come to Pakistan unless there is political stability and terrorist incidents do not take place. He noted that during the past year, a very large number of terrorist attacks took place in Pakistan. He also noted that climate change was a huge challenge for Pakistan.&#160; &#160;

Senior analyst P J Mir said the question is "What kind of planning was done while building the city that it could not sustain a calamity". He said: "This happened because we did not plan for bad times". He said the visit was needed for "appeasement" but the prime minister should not be taking every burden. He said the prime minister should delegate the authority to the chief minister. He appreciated that the disaster-stricken people were being provided "relief".&#160;

Javed Siddique, a senior journalist and analyst, was of the view that the prime minister's decision to visit Gwadar should be appreciated because it is a place of "strategic importance" and "the future of our trade is linked with it". He expressed the view that Balochistan needed a "healing touch" as the Baloch nationalist parties keep complaining that Balochistan has been ignored and some "anti-Pakistan foreign forces also exploit such issues" which has created "issues of militancy and insurgency" in the area. He said in this context the Prime Minister took a timely step by giving priority to Balochistan. He emphasised that the federal and provincial governments should show that "Balochistan is their primary concern".

Rehman questioned whether Asif Ali Zardari, the co-chairman of the Pakistan Peoples Party [PPP], who is the presidential candidate of the parties in the government was in a "comfortable position" for his election on 9 March. Mohmand said the PPP has contacted various parties and was in a strong position in Sindh while having sufficient support in the Punjab and Balochistan assemblies and the National Assembly.

Mir said Zardari was in a comfortable position as he had the numbers. He appreciated that PPP and PML-N which were "arch-rivals" have joined together "for the sake of the country".

Siddique said Zardari would be elected the president comfortably and recalled that in the past when Zardari was the president of the country he conducted his office "very smoothly". He was of the view that Zardari, as president, would try to play a role in bringing the opposition and the PML-N government closer.

Source: PTV News, Islamabad, in Urdu 1500 GMT 5 Mar 24

State Minister of Finance and a Board Member of the Pension Fund, Eyob Tekalign, said that a decision had been made to reinstate payments to affected pensioners.

&#8220;He clarified that this decision was made on political grounds, recognising the lack of a formal mechanism to facilitate pension disbursements when contributions were not received over the past three years,&#8221; it reported.&#160;

It added that following the decision by the federal government, pensioners would receive their pensions in the coming weeks.&#160;

In June last year, hundreds of retired civil servants in Tigray protested in the capital Mekele against interrupted pensions following the war.&#160;

Reports last February said 380 pensioners had died due to hunger and health issues since they lacked money.

Source: Addis Standard website, Addis Ababa, in English,19 Mar 24

"By God's grace, it has been confirmed that 10 apostate soldiers were killed, while six others were wounded in the attack," the website said without mentioning when it occurred.&#160;

"Mujahideen forces also seized a PKM machine gun and other military equipment from the apostate militias during the attack," it added.

The Somali government did not immediately comment on the militant group's claim.&#160;

It comes days after al-Shabab said it killed 13 members of the Somali intelligence agency near the southern town of Afgoye.&#160;

The militant group has increased attacks on the Somali forces during the holy month of Ramadan, despite a heightened military operation against its fighters in the southern and central regions of Somalia.&#160;

Source: Calamada website in Somali 21 Mar 24

&#8220;Politicians attending the meeting in Garowe, who are strongly opposed to the amendments, are expected to issue a communique [at the end of the summit],&#8221; the radio said.

Two former presidents, several lawmakers and the leader of Puntland regional state are attending the talks. The radio did not say when the meeting will end.&#160;

The talks started on the same day that Somalia MPs were concluding debate on article four of the provisional constitution.&#160;

Somali President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud on 22 March criticised his predecessors Mohamed Abdullahi Farmajo&#160;and Sharif&#160;Sheikh&#160;Ahmed for opposing the amendments.

Farmajo and Ahmed are concerned that the amendments &#8211; that are being pushed by the presidency &#8211; seek to change the country's system of governance.

Source: Radio Kulmiye, Mogadishu, in Somali 1030 GMT 23 Mar 24

&#8220;The ten hostages, including a five-month-old infant and six women, were released on Wednesday evening. They were handed over to the military authorities and then transferred to Bunia[north-eastern Ituri Province],&#8221; the report said.

The militia abducted the ten former hostages after a clash with the Zairean militia last week.

Codeco, whose members belong to the Lendu community, frequently carries out attacks against security forces and civilians.&#160;

The group has been operating in the Djugu region in north-eastern DR Congo since December 2017.&#160;

Source: Radio Okapi (Kinshasa), Kinshasa, in French 22 Mar 24

The report, which was aired towards the end of the nearly-two-hour-long Main Broadcast programme on Belarus 1 and its international satellite version Belarus 24 under the caption "Special election", abounded in such epithets as "historic" and "unprecedented" with regard to the vote and turnout, respectively.

"Donbas residents are taking part in Russian presidential elections for the first time. To each of them it is more than just a vote. It is about choosing peace and a calm future for their children. Which is why everyone turns up," the female presenter said. &#160;&#160;

"The turnout is unprecedented despite the terror from Ukraine, shelling and drone activity in the air," the male presenter chimed in.

Most of the video footage produced by the Belarusian TV crew dispatched to Donbas came from Mariupol and some from recently occupied Avdiivka.

Belarus 1 reporter Kseniya Lebedzeva drew a comparison between the liberation of Donbas from German Nazis in 1943, commemorated at the Saur Mohyla memorial complex, and the fall of Donbas areas to Russian troops. "The city defended its right to live two years ago," Lebedzeva said, referring to Mariupol.&#160;

Local residents and voters in Mariupol were shown describing their war ordeal, expressing hopes for the war to end and hailing the Russian election as a vote for the "future of our country".&#160;

"Not just families but whole working collectives came to cast their ballots," Lebedzeva observed, adding that "Ukraine keeps shelling the long-suffering city but local people have only grown more united." &#160;

She cited 86% as the turnout figure for the whole of the DPR, "one of the highest in the Russian election".

A polling station chairwoman was shown saying that the election enabled DPR residents to "move forward together with Russia".

According to Lebedzeva, observers from Chile, Mexico, USA, France, Italy and Cameroon monitored the vote in the DPR and were impressed.

A man captioned as "French observer Emery Francis d'Artagnan" was shown saying this about the vote: "I saw that everything was organised excellently, everything is great, everything works. Impossible to find fault with anything."&#160;

Coverage then shifted to Avdiivka, with the correspondent saying: "The Armed Forces of Ukraine have only just suffered a shameful defeat but people here are already flocking to elect the president." An elderly woman was shown signing for a ballot paper at a polling station.

DPR electoral commission chief Vladimir Vysotsky was shown at the end of the report saying that the main factor behind the high turnout was "our voters' belief in Russia and our belief that we shall win".

Source: Belarus 24 TV, Minsk, in Russian 1800 GMT 17 Mar 24

"According to the list of candidates published by the Constitutional Court, there will be 2,350 candidates for 113 seats in the forthcoming legislative elections," the website said.&#160;

The candidates come from 19 political parties, 60 independent groups and two political groupings.&#160;

Some party leaders led by Together Alliance party leader Tchasona Traore, however, criticised the court for rushing to publish the list of candidates, citing errors.

Others accused the court of delaying to publish the lists.

It remains unclear why the legislative and regional elections, initially scheduled for December 2023, were postponed.

Source: Radio France Internationale website, Paris, in French 25 Mar 24

The initial court session was presided over by Judge Iman Afshari, a hardline cleric who is notorious for issuing execution orders against political prisoners.

A prosecutor read out the indictment against the singer, according to the report, without elaborating on the charges against him.

The judge adjourned the trial to an undated second session to "allow" Tataloo time to prepare his defence.&#160;

Known for his unconventional views, the rapper supported the hardliner Ebrahim Raisi during the 2017 presidential elections, but later turned his back on the ruling hardliners.&#160;

Widely popular among sectors of Iran's Z-generation, Tataloo left Iran in 2018, initially for Georgia before residing in neighbouring Turkey, where he is alleged to have committed multiple offences.&#160;

Iranian officials announced on 6 December that Tataloo had been "extradited" by Turkish authorities to their Iranian counterparts, after private lawsuits had been lodged by Iranian teenagers and their families against the singer.&#160;

A report by the hardline Fars News Agency in January cited an "informed" judiciary source as saying that Tataloo will be facing an array of accusations, including "promotion of sexual misconduct" among teenagers and founding gambling networks.&#160;

Source: Mizan news agency, Tehran, in Persian 1041 GMT 4 Mar 24

Suluhu made the pledge during a phone call to delegates attending a women&#8217;s clean cooking conference in the capital Dodoma.&#160;

&#8220;My pledge to you is that I will ensure that a greater proportion of Tanzanians use clean cooking energy,&#8221; she said.

At least 90% of households in Tanzania currently use firewood and charcoal for cooking.&#160;

The government has set up a committee and a clean energy fund to roll out subsidies to firms in the sector.&#160;

Tanzania hopes to roll back the effects of climate change and improve health outcomes with the use of clean cooking energy. &#160;

Source: Uhuru, Dar es Salaam, in Swahili on 11 Mar 24

"In Lower Jubba region, further details have emerged of yesterday's [21 March] attack on a military base in Bar Sanguni area on the outskirts of Kismayo town where at least five apostate soldiers were killed and nine others injured," the radio said in its 0500 GMT news bulletin.&#160;

"Those killed and wounded include army commanders. Mujahiden seized weapons such as AK47 rifles, RPGs [Rocket-propelled grenades] and other military equipment in the attack," it added.&#160;

The state-owned&#160;Jubbaland TV reported on 21 that the regional administration forces backed by the Somali army have "inflicted huge casualties" on al-Shabab militants who tried to attack Bar Sanguni military base.&#160;&#160;

Both the government troops and al-Shabab had clashed in the area several times in the past, with each of them claiming victory over the other.

Source: Radio Andalus in Somali 0500 GMT 22 Mar 24

"The provisional toll issued by the National Disaster Risk Management Office (BNGRC) reports 11 dead, two missing, two injured and over 7,100 people affected," the report said.&#160;

It also said&#160;that the victims either drowned or were swept away by the water, adding that three of the victims were children.&#160;

The flooding caused serious material damage, cut off roads and made bridges collapse. This cut the region off from the rest of the country.&#160;

Cyclone Gamane made landfall on 27 March hitting the regions of Diane, Sava and Analanjirofo. It is forecast to move southwards.&#160;

The island nation of Madagascar is frequently hit by cyclones. On 4 January, a storm killed five in the south.&#160;

Source: Madagascar Tribune website, Antananarivo, in French 28 Mar 24

Broadcasting and Telecommunication Principal Secretary Edward Kisiang&#8217;ani said the government was keen on partnering with the private sector to connect over 8 million homes to the internet between 2026 and 2027.

&#8220;We will now use the power lines and push fibre into the meter boxes. This will hasten the process and increase connectivity,&#8221; Kisiang&#8217;ani was quoted as saying at a National Public Key Infrastructure (NPKI) forum.

He said the initiative was a change in strategy from the previous plan to build 100,000 kilometres of fibre optic cable across the country.&#160;

The government had pledged to roll out 25,000 Wi-Fi hotspots nationwide and establish 1,450 digital hubs in each ward in the previous plan.&#160;

&#8220;Instead of talking about kilometres, we need to talk of homesteads,&#8221; Kisiang&#8217;ani said.&#160;

Kenya has among the most fastest internet speeds in the region and hosts some of the biggest multinational tech firms.&#160;

Source: People Daily, Nairobi, in English 20 Mar 24

IRNA said the crossing had halted its operations following a strike by Iraqi lorry drivers transporting export goods from Iraq to Iran.&#160;

Mehran Governor Ali Abbas Shafiei told IRNA that Iran's Ilam Province Governor-General Hassan Bahramnia travelled to Iraq &#160;for negotiations with Wasit Governor Muhammad Jamil al-Mayahi on the reopening of the crossing.&#160;

The two sides decided to reopen the border following the joint border committee's meeting.&#160;

The crossing is an important point connecting the two countries and is used by exporters as wells as pilgrims to holy cities in both countries.&#160;

Source: Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) website, Tehran, in Persian 1145 GMT 16 Mar 24

Jaishankar arrived in Singapore on 23 March for a three-day visit.

He also discussed strengthening bilateral ties during his meetings with Singapore Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, Foreign Minister Vivian Balakrishnan and other senior ministers.&#160;

According to&#160;a statement from India's Foreign Ministry, the two countries discussed deepening cooperation in many areas including fintech, digitalisation, food security and green economy.

From Singapore, Jaishankar is scheduled to visit the Philippines and Malaysia.&#160;

According to the ministry statement, the foreign minister's tour will provide an opportunity to enhance engagement on regional issues of mutual concern.

Source: The Hindu website, Chennai, in English 0815 GMT 25 Mar 24

&#8220;It is wrong for Channel 4 [News] to give a platform to criminals. The RNC is a terrorist group that carried out grenade attacks, which killed innocent civilians," the Rwanda government spokesperson, Yolande Makolo, said, adding that Ingabire was a convict.

"Victoire Ingabire was working with the genocidal Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda (FDLR) group on plans to overthrow the government. She was convicted in a trial that included the testimony of her accomplices.&#8221;

Makolo was responding to Ali and Ingabire, who told the UK media outlet that Rwanda was not safe to resettle asylum seekers.

Ingabire is the president of the Development and Liberty for All (DALFA-Umurinzi) party and has publicly opposed the controversial deal between Rwanda and the UK.&#160;

Source: IGIHE website, Kigali, in Kinyarwanda 21 Mar 24

"In reality, these nine subcontracting companies belonging to the Russian shareholders of Kazakh of the ERG Group that operate in four mines of DR Congo, hold markets worth hundreds of millions of dollars," the director-general of the Authority for Regulation of Subcontracts (ARSP), Miguel Katemb Kashal, said during a press conference.&#160;

He added that in addition to Kazakh, the authorities dealt with with the Canadian company Barrick and the Chinese company Sicomines the same way in the past.&#160;

Kashal further said that the eliminated contracts of the Russian companies, which were focused on the mining of copper and cobalt in south-eastern DR Congo, would be handed over to companies controlled by DR Congolese firms.

The development comes after the DR Congolese government recently denied that it had signed a military agreement with Russia.

Source: Radio France Internationale, Paris, in French 12 Mar 24

Jamaat Nusrat al-Islam wal-Muslimin (JNIM) published the claim on 30 March via its channels on Chirpwire Telegram.&#160;

The statement said JNIM militants targeted a military vehicle between the towns of Diabaly and Nampala, inflicting unspecified casualties among soldiers on board.

The group published three images of a destroyed vehicle to support the claim.

Last month, the&#160;group accused the Malian military and allied Russian paramilitaries of massacring civilians along the same road in Segou.

The latest statement was numbered 107 and was attributed to JNIM's so-called Macina area of operations.&#160;

Source: Telegram messaging service in Arabic 1500 GMT 30 Mar 24

In an earlier report, al-Shabab said it killed nine in the attack, but an update by Radio Andalus said that senior commanders were among the casualties.

"It has been confirmed that 13 apostates, among them senior commanders, [were killed], while nine others were wounded," the radio said.&#160;

The group claimed to have seized three guns and ammunition from the security forces.&#160;

Pro-al-Shabab websites have also&#160;published graphic photos&#160;allegedly taken in the aftermath of battle, showing the bodies of security officers.

State-owned and independent media outlets have yet to mention the reported attack.

The Somali spy agency has special forces that regularly carry out anti-al-Shabab operations.&#160;

The ambush comes amid increased militant attacks in the country.

Source: Radio Andalus in Somali 0500 GMT 19 Mar 24

The soldiers were paraded in the village of Ilbete outside Bardhere town, according to the station.&#160;

&#8220;I am grateful to Allah and I repented to Him. I am currently in Ilbete. I was in Eritrea for five years to receive military training and four months in Mogadishu after returning from Asmara. No-one has forced me to defect,&#8221; one of the alleged defectors said.

&#8220;I am from El Waq district and now in Ilbete area to repent after I ditched the apostate group. I joined government forces in early 2023,&#8221; a second said.

The defectors called on their former colleagues to join al-Shabab.

The government did not comment on the group&#8217;s claim. &#160;

Al-Shabab often claims parading defected government forces from different regions in Somalia.&#160;

Source: Radio Andalus in Somali on 31 Mar 24

"The events in Gaza have shown what injustice and darkness prevail over the world. The Western world, which claims to advocate for human rights and the like, has shown that darkness dominates their lives, thoughts, and actions," he said, addressing a gathering in Tehran&#160;on the first day of the Iranian new year.

Khamenei's speech was broadcast live on&#160;state-run rolling news channel IRINN and IRINN2,&#160;foreign-facing English-language Press TV and state broadcaster's Network One TV on 20 March.&#160;

He said Western support for Israel validated the necessity of strengthening the "resistance front" in the region, which "must become stronger day by day".

He said the resistance front must confront "the ongoing oppression by Zionist criminals" against Palestinians and their supporters.&#160;

Khamenei&#160;said that in light of the Gaza conflict, both Western powers and regional states have become aware of "the true capacities of the resistance front".&#160;

"The US sought to take control of whole region's issues" to no avail, he said, adding that the "resistance groups" have "disrupted all of America's calculations" and that the US has no choice but to leave the region.

Khamenei said Israel "faces not only difficulties in defending itself but also struggles to extricate itself from the crisis", and is "trapped in a Gaza quagmire", leading to defeat whether it stays or leaves.

Source: Islamic Republic of Iran News Network (IRINN), Tehran, in Persian 1340 GMT 20 Mar 24

Kim Song-nam, director of the international department at the Workers' Party, made the comments in a meeting with Wang Yi in Beijing on 23 March, KCNA reported on 25 March.&#160;

Wang said he is certain their friendly ties will advance under the strategic leadership of their leaders and said Beijing will bolster strengthen "strategic communication and tactical cooperation" with Pyongyang to guard their common interests, according to KCNA.&#160;

The North Korean delegation also met Wang Huning, a member of the standing committee of the political bureau of the Chinese Communist Party, and Liu Jianchao, the minister of the party's international liaison department and Cai Qi, a senior party official, during their visit.

The North Korean delegation was in Beijing for the first leg of his three-nation trip, which will also take them to Vietnam and Laos.

Source: KCNA website, Pyongyang, in Korean 0300 GMT 25 Mar 24

It said the arrests started on 26 March, when 20 students were arrested in the capital Bamako and the southern town of Sikasso as they held a protest against a decision to ban the student association.

"My brother was called on the phone. That helped locate him and he was arrested by men dressed in civilian clothes," an unidentified student told RFI.&#160;

Others are now living in hiding but optimistic that the junta's decision to ban the AEEM will be lifted.&#160;

The military rulers &#160;banned the association on 13 March, accusing it of being behind violence in schools and universities.

Source: Radio France Internationale website, Paris, in French 30 Mar 24

"Mujahidin commanders have confirmed to Radio Andalus that the explosion killed 11 members of the Kenyan infidels and wounded eight others," the station said in its 11:00 GMT news bulletin.&#160;

Privately-owned Kenyan broadcaster Citizen TV reported on 25 March that three police officers and a civilian were killed in the attack. It said 14 others were injured.

The attack came the same day al-Shabab claimed to have seized a village in the coastal Lamu County after a deadly attack on a police post in the area.&#160;

The group's attacks against Kenyan security forces and civilians have increased since the beginning of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan.

Source: Radio Andalus in Somali 1100 GMT 26 Mar 24

Jamaat Nusrat al-Islam wal Muslimin (JNIM) made these claims in a single statement issued via its account on Telegram and Chirpwire on 18 March.&#160;

The statement said that on 13 March JNIM militants stormed a Burkinabe army barracks in "Bala" (possibly Boala) in the Centre-Nord Boulsa region, killing 18 "enemy" personnel.&#160;

Local media reported a deadly military airstrike on "terrorists" near Boala on 13 March, although there was no mention of a militant attack in the area on that day.&#160;

JNIM also claimed that on 14 March it killed four soldiers in an attack on army forces in Kalambaogo in the Centre-Nord Kaya region.&#160;

The statement reported two more attacks both also said to have taken place on 14 March.

In one of these, JNIM said it killed three pro-government militia members in an unspecified type of operation in "Basi" in the south-western Bobo-Dioulasso province. JNIM had previously claimed to have killed 10 pro-government militia members during an attack in "Basi" on 13 March.

The other attack claimed in the 18 March statement allegedly targeted a Burkinabe military vehicle between "Tagoure" and "Basra" (possibly Bossora in the south-western Hauts-Bassins region), which JNIM said completely destroyed the vehicle and killed those onboard.&#160;

JNIM said it seized several motorcycles and assorted weapons and ammunition in these attacks, with accompanying photos showing some of this purported loot, as well as an image of a wrecked army vehicle.&#160;

The statement was numbered 137 and was attributed to JNIM's "Burkina" area of operation.&#160;

Source: Chirpwire social media platform in Arabic 1140 GMT 18 Mar 24

"From 19 to 20 March 2024, the defence and security forces led a sweep-up operation in the Dolbel area up to the border with Mali," said a statement signed by the Niger defence minister, Lt Gen Salifou Mody, on 21 March and read on state-run TV Tele Sahel.

It said that during the operation, an army unit was ambushed by around 100 militants who had a combined force of improvised explosive devices (IEDs) and "kamikaze vehicles".&#160;

The statement also indicated that "despite the aggressive response", 23 soldiers were killed, and 17 others wounded, adding that "about 30 terrorists were neutralised".&#160;

Since a military coup in July 2023, the security situation in Niger has deteriorated and militant attacks increased.&#160;

Source: Tele Sahel, Niamey, in French 2000 GMT 21 Mar 24

Mohammad Eslami said the run-off polls would be organised in 21 constituencies, out of 208 nationwide, which include Tehran, Mashhad, Shiraz, Tabriz, Zanjan, Karaj and Kermanshah. Candidates are going to compete over 44 seats.&#160;

Eslami noted that the polls would be electronically conducted in eight constituencies, including in the capital Tehran. &#160;

Iranians went to the polls on 1 March to elect 290 MPs as well as members of the leadership watchdog, the Assembly of Experts, in the first elections since the 2022 nationwide protests. The elections were marked by a 41% turnout, the lowest since the establishment of the Islamic Republic in 1979.

With most reformist and moderate candidates disqualified from running, the conservatives held the majority of seats as expected, with the main rivalries now falling within that camp.

Iran's election headquarters&#160;said on 4 March&#160;that 245 out of 290 legislators had made their way into parliament, with the remainder going to run-offs in April-May.&#160;

See: Explainer: What are the main takeaways from Iran's 2024 elections?

Source: Tasnim news agency website, Tehran, in Persian 1203 GMT 18 Mar 24

The report noted that the government and the main ruling Liberal Democratic Party are in favour of easing the country's strict guidelines on arms exports.&#160;

Kishida said in the Diet, Japan's parliament, on 6 March that Japan needs to have aircraft capable of defending the country. He also said there needs to be a framework for direct transfers of aircraft to a third country to make international joint development a success, the report added.

Japan has been developing the aircraft with Britain and Italy, it added.&#160;

Kishida added that such a framework would increase the country's security and that would serve Japan's national interest, NHK World reported.

Source: NHK World website, Tokyo, in English 0800 GMT 6 Mar 24

