"It means that the West has always tried to exaggerate the issue, instead of genuinely investigating the crimes. They had gone there [Afghanistan] to commit crimes. The soliders [deployed there] were told that people would be killed, and they [the soldiers] would &#160;[also] be killed there. Whatever happened had been pledged and agreed," he said.&#160;

"In the beginning of the assignment [the invasion of Afghanistan], killing [people] was not a crime from their perspective. The reason that they [the West] are now talking of holding judicial trials [to investigate war crimes] is their internal divergences," he added.

Bezhanpour stated that the West, especially the US and the UK, are gearing up to return to Afghanistan.&#160;

"In fact, American and the British officials are in consultation with Europeans about [their possible] return to Afghanistan. However, the Europeans argued that they had gone to Afghanistan some years ago, but failed to achieve what they had aimed for," said Bezhanpour.

Political commentator Aziz Stanikzai who joined the debate from Kabul, via video link, said: "You know better that the West and the US, in the lead, entered Afghanistan 22 years ago to launch a vague campaign against extremists or those who had targeted the US towers. That time, it was heard and noticed that it were Arabs who had masterminded and implemented it [ti 9/11 attacks]."

Describing the UK inquiry into the war crimes allegation as "a propaganda", Stanikzai said: "Anyway, it is a propaganda."

"Crimes had been committed in Afghanistan. Not only the British, but Germans had also martyred 97 children and injured hundreds of others in Kunduz Province. Nobody has so far been put on trial. Nobody has been held accountable for it," he added.&#160;

Meanwhile, political pundit Sami Ullah Ahmadzai accused Americans of committing war crimes in Afghanistan during their 20-year-long military presence.

"Under the pretext of fighting terrorism, they had invaded Afghanistan. They stayed in Afghanistan for 20 years and committed crimes which were not confined to only one to two individuals. Americans, claiming to fight terrorism, came to Afghanistan primarily to achieve their own goals," he said.

"One of the tactics Americans used at the Bonn Conference was to establish the Afghan National Army, police and security forces. Americans at the Bonn Conference established the three organisations to reduce its casualties in the battlefield," claimed Ahmadzai .&#160;

Concluding, he said that such inquiries cannot hold accountable the leaders who had ordered deployment of forces to Afghanistan, which resulted in the perpetration of the "crimes". Afghan commentators appearing on the private Ariana News TV's&#160;Tahawol (Change) debate programme&#160;on 27 March discussed the allegations levelled by UK's Minister for Veterans' Affairs, Johnny Mercer, that members of Britain's SAS (Special Air Service) were engaged in "war crimes" during their mission in Afghanistan.&#160;

A report by the Guardian newspaper&#160;said that the chair of the UK's Afghanistan inquiry had ordered Mercer to reveal the source of his allegations against the British soldiers. The minister had been given a ten-day ultimatum to do so or face a potential prison sentence.

Speaking on the programme online, Norway-based political commentator Rahmat Ullah Bezhanpour said: "At that time [refers to US-led forces' invasion of Afghanistan in 2001], a large contingent of troops from the West were deployed in Afghanistan and around 60,000 military personnel started their operations there under the pretext of combatting terrorism."

