Amidst a chorus of ecstatic comments on President Vladimir Putin's address to the Federal Assembly, Alexei Tsydenov, head of the Republic of Buryatia, has said that Putin's speech covered "everything that is relevant to us," singling out measures to boost healthcare, education, environmental protection and tourism. (ulan.mk.ru website, Ulan-Ude, 1211 gmt 29 Feb 24)&#160;

Igor Kobzev, governor of Irkutsk Region, has highlighted Putin's commitment to supporting servicemen returning from the "special military operation" and using their "invaluable experience" to educate the young generation. He also praised Putin's initiatives to support small and medium businesses, which are developing strongly in Irkutsk Region. (altairk.ru website, Irkutsk, 1410 gmt 29 Feb 24;&#160;i38.ru website, Irkutsk, 1 Mar 24)

And Alexander Osipov, governor of Transbaikal Territory, has said that Putin's focus on family, youth and training of personnel touches on "everything that is important for Transbaikal Territory" and will spur the region's development. (mkchita.ru website, Chita, 1211 gmt 29 Feb 24)

Amongst many references to East Siberia in his speech, Putin noted plans to create an all-year zero-pollution holiday resort on Lake Baikal by 2030 as part of Russia's "5 Seas and Lake Baikal" domestic tourism drive, and the inclusion of Transbaikal Territory in a pilot project for the long-term preservation of cultural heritage. (ulan.mk.ru website, Ulan-Ude, 1314 gmt 29 Feb 24;&#160;mkchita.ru website, Chita, 1102 gmt 29 Feb 24)&#160;

Putin's proposal to write off two-thirds of each region's debt to the federal budget translates into a 19bn rouble (approximately $207m at the current exchange rate) win for Transbaikal Territory, which will invest the money in local infrastructure projects. Meanwhile, on the back of growing corporate tax revenue, Transbaikal Territory last year paid off all its commercial loans. Locally generated revenue in the region's consolidated budget amounted to 91.8bn roubles in 2023. (mkchita.ru website, Chita, 1152 gmt 29 Feb 24;&#160;zab.ru website, Chita, 0038 gmt 26 Feb 24)&#160;

Sri Lankan ambassador visits Buryatia&#160;

Sri Lanka's ambassador to Russia, Janitha Abeywickrema Liyanage, has paid a working visit to Buryatia, where she held meetings with Alexei Tsydenov, head of the republic, the tourism minister, and university leaders. Cooperation in tourism, education and oriental medicine were discussed, as well as the potential for future trade links and the organisation of a Russian-Sri Lankan Buddhist Association. &#160;(ulan.mk.ru website, Ulan-Ude, 0404 gmt 27 Feb 24)&#160;

Chita bans Navalny rally

Having initially approved an application from the Civic Solidarity public movement to hold a rally in memory of deceased opposition leaders Alexei Navalny and Boris Nemtsov, the mayor's office of Chita has "hastily cancelled it" after news of the event spread on social media. The official reason for rejecting the application was Navalny's involvement in "extremist activities," though sources are speculating that the city administration "got it in the neck from someone" following its original decision. The rally was called to express support for "civil society, the rule of law, and the protection of freedoms and human rights." (sibreal.org website, a project of Radio Free Europe, Prague, 28 Feb 24)&#160;

Borzya petition against mayor&#160;

Residents of Borzya, Transbaikal Territory's third biggest town, are organising a petition demanding the removal of the town's mayor, Vladimir Nekhamkin, citing "unsatisfactory performance of his duties." This winter alone, there have been "over 20" accidents in the town's heating systems, causing residents to "freeze in their apartments" with no water supply. Meanwhile, electricity bills have risen by "many times," the town's roads are in a parlous state, and it is "impossible" to walk around safely due to stray dogs. "Our patience has run out," said local resident Marina Altayeva. Signed by 54 residents so far, the petition will be taken to the prosecution service and the fed&#1077;ral authorities if regional officials fail to act. (zab.ru website, Chita, 0432 gmt 29 Feb 24;&#160;chita.ru website, Chita, 0937 gmt 2 Mar 24)&#160;

Buryatia foreign travel ban&#160;

Buryatia's People's Khural has become the first regional parliament in Russia to formally prohibit foreign travel for key officeholders. Passed unanimously and in line with recent amendments to federal law, the Khural's decision obliges chairman Vladimir Pavlov and his two deputies to give up their passports as elected officials possessing "absolutely secret information or information of special importance." (baikal-daily.ru website, 0751 gmt 27 Feb 24)&#160;

The People's Khural has also blocked a proposal by Alexei Tsydenov, the head of Buryatia, to abolish direct elections of the mayor of Ulan-Ude. Communist Party deputy Viktor Malyshenko said the proposal would have an "adverse impact on people's trust in the election procedure" in a city with "many unresolved problems." Tsydenov's proposal and accompanying PR campaign had "sparked outrage" amongst residents of Ulan-Ude. (sibreal.org website, a project of Radio Free Europe, Prague, 27 Feb 24)

Power generation plans&#160;

The Russian Energy Ministry has announced the results of a competition for the construction of new power generation capacities in southeastern Siberia. The winning projects include the completion of a 65MW expansion to Ulan-Ude's TETs-2 power station, which was mothballed following the collapse of the Soviet Union and will require 30bn roubles of investment by 2030. In Irkutsk, two 230MW units will be built at the Irkutskaya TETs-11 heat and power station, with start-up scheduled for the end of 2028.&#160;(ulan.mk.ru website, Ulan-Ude, 1416 gmt 1 Mar 24)

Meanwhile, state nuclear energy corporation Rosatom has mooted the possibility of building a small nuclear power station in Transbaikal Territory to help address a power deficit that could arise as early as 2026 if the region's planned investment projects go ahead. To be sited at Mogochi or Makkaveyevo, the station could begin generating electricity by 2033. The Transbaikal Territory authorities have previously raised the possibility of building a nuclear power station near Chita. (chita.ru website Chita, 1005 gmt 28 Feb 24)

Record grain exports&#160;

Grain exports via the Zabaikalsk border crossing in Transbaikal Territory reached 984,200 tonnes last year &#8211; an increase of 2.4 times compared to 2022. Russian grain is facilitating the modernisation of the grain industry and promoting economic development in the neighbouring Chinese province of Inner Mongolia. The grain rail transport terminal at Zabaikalsk was formally opened in 2022. A 12-year contract for the supply of 70m tonnes of Russian grain to China was signed in Beijing last autumn, and regular deliveries via Zabaikalsk began during the winter. (chita.ru website, Chita, 1353 gmt 2 Mar 24)&#160;

Cossack Cadet Corps

The government of Irkutsk Region has approved plans to establish a Cossack Cadet Corps &#8211; a new state educational organisation tasked with educating young people in the "spirit of patriotism, civil responsibility and readiness to serve the Fatherland." While the region's schools already have 24 Cossack classes providing extracurricular activities for 475 pupils, the Cadet Corps will offer a full educational experience "geared towards the spiritual and moral values of Russian Cossackdom" with a view to supplying future military cadres. The curriculum will include basic military training, the history of Cossackdom, the foundations of Orthodox culture, games, songs, and the Cossack sword dance. (altairk.ru website, Irkutsk, 07800 gmt 27 Feb 24)&#160;

Osipov's beard&#160;

In an online poll to establish the greatest achievement of Alexander Osipov in his five years as governor of Transbaikal Territory, the most popular of the multiple-choice answers was "He has appointed the weakest government in the entire history of the region." The second most popular answer, selected by 26% of respondents, was "He has grown a beard," while 5% agreed that Osipov has "discovered that Transbaikal Territory is the cradle of civilisation", and only 1% believed that he has "boosted the region's status in the eyes of the federal centre." (zab.ru website, Chita, 1401 gmt 29 Feb 24)

In another poll by the zab.ru website on attitudes towards state media coverage of life in Transbaikal Territory, 63% of respondents selected the reply "nothing but lies and window-dressing bearing no relation to reality." (zab.ru website, Chita, 1438 gmt 27 Feb 24)

Source: BBC Monitoring 3 Mar 24

Two years ago, the whole world saw the true meaning of our battle here in Ukraine.&#160;

Everyone for whom it was, unfortunately, just "another war" saw it.&#160;

They saw what kind of war it is. That Ukraine is defending not only its state border and sovereignty.

For us, this is a war to defend Ukraine and everything that makes people human.

That is why this war is of global significance. This is a war for the right to exist for our state and, at the same time, for the right to life for every person. It is a war for dignity for our people and for every nation that seeks its own destiny. This is a war so that no one dares to become a beast towards others.

When our warriors drove Russia out of Bucha, Irpin, Borodyanka, the entire Kyiv Region, and then Sumy and Chernihiv regions, everyone could see that these were victories not only of Ukrainian courage and weapons, but also of human morality.&#160;

Ukrainians then began to restore normal life wherever Russia had brought death and torture, looting and sadism.

And our people killed by the occupiers, whose bodies were on the streets of Bucha, were evidence that no one in the world should stay away from this battle. Because it is here, in Ukraine, defending our people, our lives, our state, that humanity is prevailing.

To unleash such acts of aggression against others, Russia first destroyed its own morality and made violence and hatred its ideology. Such systems don't just stop. Force stops them. Unity stops them. Determination and understanding what exactly they want to destroy stops them.

I am proud of everyone who dedicates their lives to ensuring that the life of our entire Ukraine is preserved.

I thank everyone in the world who really helps us.&#160;

And may the whole world never forget the cost of this battle and the evil we are holding back here on our land. Let us now observe a minute of silence in memory of all our people whose lives were taken by the occupiers.

Thank you.

Glory to our strong people, our warriors! Glory to all who defend humanity and life!&#160;

The original is here.

Source: Ukrainian president's website, Kyiv, in English 1357 GMT 31 Mar 24

