On 18 March, the NATO Baltic Air Policing Mission Detachment aircraft were scrambled to identify and escort one IL-20 flying from Kaliningrad into international airspace and then back. It had no pre-filed flight plan, the onboard transponder was switched off and the crew was not maintaining radio communication with the regional air traffic control centre.&#160;

On 19 March, the NATO air policing fighter aircraft were scrambled to intercept one IL-76 flying from Kaliningrad to mainland Russia in international airspace. It had no flight a plan, the onboard transponder was on and the crew was maintaining radio communication with the regional air traffic control centre.

On 19 March, the NATO fighter jets identified and escorted one IL-20 flying from Kaliningrad and back through international airspace. It had no pre-filed flight plan, the onboard transponder was off, no radio contact.&#160;&#160;

On 19 March, the NATO Air Policing fighter jets were scrambled to intercept one SU-24MR flying in international airspace from Kaliningrad to mainland Russia without the flight plan, its onboard transponder off, not maintaining radio communication.&#160;&#160;

On 21 March, the NATO fighter jets identified and escorted one IL-20. It was flying in international airspace from Kaliningrad to the mainland of the Russian Federation without the flight plan, with its onboard transponder off, not maintaining radio communication.&#160;&#160;

Source: ELTA, Vilnius, in English 0633 GMT 26 Mar 24

Following last month's elections, Shehbaz Sharif, the younger brother of three-time prime minister Nawaz Sharif, was sworn in as the country's new prime minister on 4 March. The Taliban have not yet congratulated Sharif on his victory, but have reiterated their willingness to pursue&#160;good relations with all neighbours, including Pakistan.&#160;

Speaking on the programme, London-based analyst Habibullah Janebdar called on Sharif's administration to reconsider his country's "brutal past policies" towards Afghanistan and said that normalising ties would be in Pakistan's interests.&#160;

"But if this government, like its predecessors, lack independence, it will find it difficult to normalise relations with Afghanistan or its other neighbours," he added.&#160;

When asked what "mistakes" previous Pakistani governments had done in dealing with Afghanistan, Janebdar referred to the recent forced deportation of Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the neighbouring country's "unnecessary restrictions" on Afghan traders.

"Pakistani authorities should desist from the policy of hate towards Afghans and stop insults at borders," he added.&#160;

When asked whether the new government would be able to manage&#160;the current economic and security crisis in Pakistan, he said: "It will be very difficult to manage the crisis... They are at a crossroad. There are two possibilities. They might end up in a worse situation or attain relative stability."&#160;

Another analyst at the TV studio in Kabul, Dr Moeen Gul Samkanai, also called on the new government to normalise ties with the Taliban, saying: "Given their economic and security crisis, they should play a constructive role in trade so they can send their goods to Central Asia, and we can send ours to Indian and other markets".&#160;

"Apart from this, they should refrain from levelling accusations against the Afghan government and, instead, do their own homework," he added, in reference to repeated allegations from Pakistani authorities that militant groups have been using Afghanistan's territory to plan and conduct attacks.&#160;

When asked about the prospects of Pakistan and Afghan Taliban relations under the new government, Samkanai replied: "Civilian governments will come and go, but the strategy and policy will remain in the hands of the army."

"Civilian governments will continue playing their symbolic roles, but not strategic," he added.&#160;

When asked whether Shehbaz Sharif would be able to resolve his country's crisis, Samkanai answered: "I do not think so."

He described the controversial elections in Pakistan as "rigged" and stated: "After Nawaz [Sharif] was called from London, it was obvious that they [Pakistani army] would bring the Nawaz family to power."

"I would say there was fraud for sure," he alleged.&#160;

Commenting on the economic crisis in Pakistan, Samkanai said that Islamabad is now "stuck between China and America", adding: "China has projects there and America does not want China to implement its projects."&#160;

The other commentator, a Pakistani journalist from Islamabad, Tahir Khan stated his belief that "Afghanistan will be a big challenge" for the Shehbaz Sharif administration.

Khan advised the new government to pursue good relations with Kabul, which he said has managed to strengthen trade ties with Iran - through which the Taliban can use as an alternative transit route.&#160;

The commentator also admitted that his country is going through a "very difficult political crisis".&#160;

When asked whether the Pakistani people were satisfied with the results of the elections, Khan replied: "There is distrust. It would not be right if I were to say that yes, the public is happy."&#160;

"Apart from Nawaz Sharif's Pakistan Muslim League and, to some extent, the Pakistan People's Party, all other parties are not happy with the results of the elections," Khan added.&#160;

When asked what challenges the new government was facing, Khan listed the economic crisis at top of the challenges which Sharif's government would struggle to address, saying: "Pakistan does need international loans as its economy is not good at all."&#160;

"There is inflation. People are facing difficulties with electricity, gas and fuel prices skyrocketing," he stated, adding that "it would be very difficult" for the Shehbaz Sharif administration to manage the crisis.&#160;

Source: Shamshad TV, Kabul, in Pashto 1740 GMT 13 Mar 24

"Two weeks to the day after the assassination of Yaya Dillo, president of the PSF, the arrest of its activists and the demolition of its headquarters, Mahamat Kaka [President Gen Mahamat Idriss Deby] orders the dissolution of the PSF," Tchad One said in a post on X (formerly Twitter).&#160;

It added that the Minister of State and Minister of Territorial Administration and Decentralisation, Limane Mahamat, carried out the task of suspending the party&#8217;s activities and requesting the head of the Supreme Court Samir Anour to carry out the dissolution of the party.&#160;

The post contained a bilingual Arabic-French document dated 29 February and signed by Mahamat ordering the court to dissolve the party.&#160;

Tchad One called it the "repression of a political party" and a "first" in 34 years of "pseudo-democracy" stressing that it happened two days after President Deby asked for forgiveness for his mistakes.&#160;

The post further implied that the recent&#160;visit by French President Emmanuel Macron&#8217;s envoy Jean Marie Bockel to Chad prompted the move as he expressed France&#8217;s support and "admiration" for President Deby.&#160;

Tchad One said that alleged attempts by the government to "erase Dillo from the presidential landscape" would fail as he remained "in the hearts of all Chadians deprived of justice and change".&#160;

On 29 February, opposition leader Dillo was killed by security forces after being accused - alongside his party - of plotting to murder the head of the country's Supreme Court. He was a cousin of President Deby.&#160;

Subsequently, Chadian authorities demolished the party&#8217;s headquarters on 1 March. &#160;

Source: X (formerly Twitter) in French 13 Mar 24

The admiral's message was re-posted by the Navy's own X account. A press release was also published on 26 March on the Colombian Navy's website. &#160;&#160;

The report said that the 3,355 kg of cocaine seized were being transported in a go-fast boat in Colombia's islands department of San Andres and Providencia. It added that the seizure was the result of a combined operation between the the Colombian Navy, the Colombian Air Force and the Joint Interagency Task Force of the United States Southern Command.&#160;

According to the statement, the drug-carrying vessel was stopped by a Quick Reaction Unit from the San Andres Coast Guard Station after being chased for several miles by the Colombian Navy.

"During the procedure, the subjects crewing the vessel began evasive actions, throwing packages into the water," the report said.

The intercepted boat was crewed by five people, three of Colombian nationality, one Honduran and one Venezuelan, according to the press release. It added that, following the seizure, the vessel was taken to the San Andres Coast Guard Station dock.

The statement said that, thanks to this seizure, "more than eight million doses will not reach the streets of different countries". The report did not specify which countries.

"Largest cocaine shipment of the year seized in the Colombian Caribbean," the Colombian statement said in its headline. &#160;

Source: X (formerly Twitter) in Spanish 1611 GMT 26 Mar 24

The announcement comes amid significant unrest in north-west Syria, where TIP is based, that is threatening the standing of Islamist group Hayat Tahrir al-Sham (HTS), of which TIP is a longstanding ally.

See: Analysis: Protests shake HTS's grip on Syria rebel bastion

While the TIP statement did not refer to the anti-HTS protests in rebel-held Idlib, the bastion of HTS, it did hint at difficult circumstances facing TIP, as it called for "cohesion" and "unity".&#160;

The one-page statement in Arabic was dated 24 March 2024 and signed by TIP's top leader, "Abd al-Haqq". It was shared the following day on Telegram by a number of Syria-focused Islamist and pro-opposition accounts, including by former HTS member Abu Yahya al-Farghali.

Appointments

The statement announced the appointment of two deputies to TIP-Syria leader, Abu Omar Kawthar.&#160;

They were named as Abu Muhammad (aka Zahid Qari), identified as TIP-Syria's military commander, and someone named only as Sheikh Touba, whose honorary title of "Sheikh" suggests seniority or scholarly credentials.

Both individuals appear to be relatively unknown, with little apparent online presence in jihadist social media circles.

The statement said the decision to make these appointments came after consultations between the Shura councils of central TIP and its Syrian branch.

It also stressed the importance of communication between the central TIP leadership and its Syria chapter.

&#8220;We ask of the brothers to obey what is correct, and advise all officials in the Syrian branch to make sure to communicate with their central leadership and interact it with it righteously.&#8221;

Message on unity

The message carried an implicit warning against fragmentation, hinting at difficult times for TIP followers.

Addressing its members in Syria, the leadership told them: &#8220;At a time when Islam has become alienated, and especially the Muslims of Turkistan, who are subject to terrible persecution, we ask of you to preserve the unity of the group and strengthen cooperation between yourselves and be at peace with one another.&#8221;

It also urged them to obey TIP leadership, whilst also encouraging them to offer advice and suggestions.&#160;

Overall, the statement was vague on why the appointments were made, if they replaced existing officials or were new, and if TIP has been affected by the protests dogging its ally, HTS.&#160;

The TIP has been active in northern Syria since the early days of the Syrian conflict. It has been fighting alongside HTS, under the latter's joint operations room al-Fatah al-Mubin, while officially remaining autonomous and often trying to avoid infighting and inter-rebel friction.&#160;

The group frequently criticises China for occupying the Muslim-majority region of Xinjiang, which it calls &#8220;East Turkistan,&#8221; and for the alleged persecution of Uyghur Muslims.&#160;

In December last year, TIP set up social media accounts, but the group's media operation and outlets nevertheless continue to suffer from instability.

Source: X (formerly Twitter) in Arabic 1430 GMT 25 Mar 24

"Abakar Karimi, writer and special advisor to the assassinated president of PSF, Yaya Dillo, has left Chad after a four-day manhunt," the website wrote in a post on X (formerly Twitter).&#160;

It added that Karimi was &#8220;in the crosshairs&#8221; of ANSE for being close to Dillo and having a good knowledge of the party.&#160;

The post made no mention of his destination nor his current whereabouts.&#160;

Yaya Dillo, who was a cousin of President Mahamat Idriss Deby and possible presidential hopeful was killed on 29 February. The authorities vowed to launch an investigation into his death.

