Newly elected Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif on 5 March announced relief package for those affected by the torrential rains in Balochistan province. &#160;

The development came amid Sharif's visit to the rain-hit coastal area Gwadar. &#160;

See more: Heavy rain inundates parts of Balochistan province

Sharif announced financial compensation for the affected people including 2 million rupees [$7,156.14] each for the families of the deceased and 0.5 million rupees [$1,789] for the injured, prominent English-language newspaper Pakistan Today reported.&#160;

Sharif announced 750,000 rupees [$2,683.65] each to those whose houses have been completely destroyed by rain, while 350,000 rupees [$1,252,37] each to those whose house are partially damaged, reported Geo News, an Urdu TV news channel that generally supports Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N). &#160;

The prime minister also directed to compile a report on the damages to private properties and ordered early restoration of communication infrastructure, leading Urdu newspaper Jang reported.&#160;

The development received extensive coverage in the frontline newspapers and online media outlets. &#160;Select editorials hailed PM's visit to Balochistan.&#160;

"It's good to see that an elected PM decided to visit Gwadar a day after taking charge and went on a maiden visit to a province that has been neglected for decades," prominent English-language newspaper The News said. &#160;

"The idea of Pakistan as a federation is not to dismiss the grievances of smaller provinces but to give equal rights and autonomy to all provinces," it added. &#160;

Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif's visit to Gwadar "highlights the gravity of the situation with his announcement of a comprehensive relief package, encompassing monetary compensation for the families of the deceased, support for the injured and assistance for those whose homes have been damaged," prominent English-language newspaper The Express Tribune said. &#160;

"Amidst the sorrow for lives lost, solidarity with affected communities and a steadfast commitment to collective action are imperative," it added. &#160;&#160;

Army rejects claims of 'interference' in electoral process&#160;

The Pakistan Army on 5 March rejected "unsubstantiated allegations" of "interference" in the electoral process, the military's media wing Inter-Services Public Relations (ISPR) said. &#160;&#160;

The development came during the 263rd Corps Commanders' Conference (CCC) chaired by Chief of Army Staff (COAS) General Asim Munir at General Headquarters (GHQ) in Rawalpindi city of Punjab province. &#160;

ISPR said the "forum noted that the Armed Forces of Pakistan at a great peril to their primary responsibility, provided security environment for the conduct of GE-24 [general elections 2024] as per the given mandate, and had nothing to do with the electoral process". &#160;

However, the forum expressed "dismay that some vested small segments of polity and media especially social media have been maligning Armed Forces of Pakistan with unsubstantiated allegations of interference which is highly deplorable," ISPR said.

"It's unfortunate that rather than focusing on real issues such as good governance, economic recovery, political stability and public wellbeing, entire focus of such vested elements is on creating political instability and uncertainty by attempting to scapegoat others for their own failings," ISPR added.

The ISPR further said that the forum emphasised that "due legal processes be followed with evidence and proof rather than resorting to unconstitutional and uncalled for baseless political rhetoric and emotional outbursts".

"Forum noted with satisfaction the smooth democratic transition of power in the Centre [federal government] and provinces," ISPR said adding forum hoped that the post elections environment brings in "desired political and economic stability resulting into peace and prosperity for the people of Pakistan". &#160;&#160;

The ISRP said that forum paid rich tribute to the supreme sacrifices of Shuhadas [martyrs] including officers and men of the armed forces, Law Enforcement Agencies (LEAs) and the citizens who have laid their lives for ensuring peace and stability in the country. &#160;

"Forum resolved that terrorists, their facilitators and abettors, working on behest of hostile forces to destabilise Pakistan, will be dealt with full might of the state," ISPR said. &#160;

The ISPR further said that COAS directed commanders to "continue consolidating the gains of efforts against terrorism and militancy". &#160;

ISPR said that in line with the resolve of the honourable prime minister of Pakistan, the forum committed that "planners, instigators, abettors and perpetrators/desecrators of Shuhada Monuments and attackers of military installations on 9 May, would certainly be brought to justice under the relevant provisions of the law and Constitution".&#160;

The workers of Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) have been accused of ransacking public property and military installations following arrest of party founder, Imran Khan that day. &#160;&#160;

"The forum expressed concerns over continued repression of Kashmiris in Indian Illegally Occupied Jammu and Kashmir (India-administered Kashmir) and condemned the unabated human rights violations by India," ISPR said adding the forum reaffirmed that Pakistan shall continue to support Kashmiris "politically, diplomatically and morally at all levels".

The forum also expressed complete solidarity with the Palestinians and condemned "serious human rights violations and war crimes being perpetrated in Gaza", ISPR said. &#160;&#160;

The development received prominent and largely factual coverage in the frontline newspapers and online media outlets. &#160;

The developments were also discussed on X (formerly Twitter) in Pakistan as of 09:00 GMT on 6 March under prominent trends #AsimMunir and "Duffers". &#160;&#160;

Several posts called Army leadership as "duffers". &#160;&#160;

See more: Election body says troops to stay outside polling stations&#160;

Resolution for release of ex-PM Khan submitted to parliament &#160;

The Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) on 5 March submitted a resolution to the lower house of the parliament, the National Assembly Secretariat, seeking release of the party's founder Imran Khan and several other political leaders and journalists, local media reported. &#160;

Khan has been lodged in a jail in several cases since 5 August, 2023. &#160;

PTI leaders including Omar Ayub Khan and Asad Qaiser submitted the resolution, pro-military Urdu TV news channel Samaa TV reported. &#160;

The resolution demanded immediate release of Khan, emphasising that "he is a prominent leader of the Muslim world," the news report added.

The resolution said that cases against the PTI founder were registered to "politically victimise" him and keep him away from the masses, Urdu TV news channel ARY News reported. &#160;

Meanwhile, Qaiser said that the PTI would unite all political forces and launch a "movement" against a "rigged election", the news report added. &#160;

Separately, newly elected Chief Minister of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Ali Amin Gandapur, called on Imran Khan at Adiala Jail in Rawalpindi city of Punjab to discuss cabinet formation in the province, Ausaf, an Urdu newspaper generally critical of PML-N reported. &#160;

Khan, in the meeting, reportedly proposed 15-member provincial cabinet, the news report added. &#160;

Talking to media outside the Adiala Jail, Gandapur said that Khan will decide on "reconciliation with the establishment [reference to military establishment]" The News reported. &#160;

PTI has been accusing the establishment of interference in politics and helping the opposition oust Khan's government in April 2022. &#160;

The development received extensive coverage in the frontline newspapers and online media outlets.

"The people of the province trusted the PTI and voted for Gandapur to provide them an opportunity to serve the nation instead of satisfying their personal enmity or the party's tussle with the adversaries," prominent English-language newspaper The Frontier Post said in an editorial.

"Hence, civic groups and politicians must think about the country and the masses instead of their politics and power," it added.

Social buzz &#160;

The top trend on X in Pakistan as of 09:00 GMT on 6 March was "Article 6" which appeared in posts urging to try Chief Election Commissioner, Sikandar Sultan Raja, under Article 6 of the Constitution for "illegally" distributing PTI's reserved seats in the National and provincial assemblies among other political parties.&#160;

Source: BBC Monitoring in Urdu 0000 GMT 6 Mar 24

