The 6 February bomb attacks in the Somali capital market killed&#160;at least 12 people and wounded dozens of others.&#160;

The militant group, al-Shabab did not claim responsibility for the bombings as it is known for downplaying civilian casualties in its attacks.

Source: Somali National TV (SNTV), Mogadishu, in Somali 21 Mar 24

IS issued the claims on 14 March through an extensive roundup of its Sahel branch activities, featured in its weekly newspaper al-Naba (issue 434). This was published through the group's accounts on Telegram.&#160;

The al-Naba roundup included two claims that BBC Monitoring covered separately: the killing of an al-Qaeda commander in north-eastern Mali, and the killing of four Benin "Christians" in the same region.&#160;

Attacks in Mali

IS said that on 6 March its militants attacked a military base used by the Malian army and allied Wagner mercenaries in the village of Labbezanga in the town of Ansongo in the north-eastern Gao region.&#160;

The attack "killed and wounded many" of the enemy forces, al-Naba said, without offering details.

The newspaper featured an image to illustrate the attack, showing a militant firing at an apparent army base from afar.&#160;

The publication moved to relay an attack on Tuareg militiamen, known as the&#160;Movement for the Salvation of the Azawad (MSA), in eastern Mali.&#160;

It said on 5 March, IS militants attacked an MSA checkpoint "north of Menaka" in eastern Mali, allegedly killing two rival fighters, "while the rest fled". The group said its militants seized a 4x4 vehicle as well as weapons and ammunition from the scene, before allegedly returning safely to their base.

IS had separately issued images from that attack on 11 March.&#160;

Al-Naba said that the following day, on 6 March, IS militants attacked a "pro-government militia" checkpoint on the Menaka-Ansongo road, allegedly killing one militia member "while the rest fled". It shared a picture said to show the slain militia fighter.&#160;

The two other attacks in Mali listed in the roundup were the killing of 19 al-Qaeda fighters, including a top commander, in Gao; and the killing of four Benin "Christians" on the Labbezanga-Ansongo road. (See here and here)

Attack in Burkina Faso&#160;

Moving to neighbouring Burkina Faso, al-Naba portrayed IS militants there as defenders of Muslims against the aggression and "criminality" of al-Qaeda fighters.

It said that on 27 February, al-Qaeda militants tried to raid and rob Muslim residents in "the village of" Gorgadji in Dori, north-eastern Burkina Faso.

This attempt, al-Naba continued, prompted IS militants to respond and attack the al-Qaeda "raiders", triggering clashes in which two al-Qaeda fighters were killed, a third was captured, "while the rest fled".&#160;

As such, al-Naba triumphantly said, IS prevented the rival militants from looting the village.&#160;

Both IS and al-Qaeda often accuse each other of starting aggressions, with each claiming to be defending Muslims against the other. While IS typically calls al-Qaeda militants "apostates" and "militiamen"; al-Qaeda calls IS members "ultra-extremists" (khawarij).&#160;

Source: al-Naba newspaper in Arabic 2355 GMT 14 Mar 24

IS issued seven photos on behalf of its so-called West Africa Province branch (ISWAP), via its accounts on Telegram on 21 March.&#160;

The photos appeared to refer to an attack in north-eastern Nigeria that IS claimed on 18 March. IS had said the attack killed and wounded a number of "African coalition" personnel, including two officers, presumably affiliated to the Multinational Joint Task Force (MNJTF). The MNJTF is tasked with fighting jihadist insurgency in the Lake Chad basin.

One photo showed an image of the purported suicide bomber, named as Abu Adam al-Nijri, a nom de guerre that suggests he was from Niger.&#160;

The set of photos concluded with a cloud of smoke which IS claims captured the moment of the suicide bombing. &#160;

Text accompanying the images added that the attack had taken place near the town of Gashagar in Borno state. In recent weeks, ISWAP has been fending off army assaults on their positions in the country's north-eastern state.

Source: Telegram messaging service in Arabic 1500 GMT 21 Mar 24

IS issued the claim on 19 March via its accounts on Telegram, and in the name of its &#8220;Central Africa Province&#8221; branch (ISCAP).

It said IS militants attacked "the village of Masusi in Beni&#8221; in eastern DR Congo, and captured and later killed the three individuals. It is unclear if IS meant the town of Masisi in the same region.&#160;

While the group did not say when the attack took place, the breaking-news stylisation of the claim suggested it happened on the same day.&#160;

A day earlier, on 18 March, ISCAP issued three separate claims for similar attacks in eastern DR Congo, including in &#8220;Masusi&#8221;, saying its militants killed a total of five &#8220;Christians&#8221; and captured another five.&#160;

Christian civilians have had the lion&#8217;s share of IS attacks in DR Congo since last year, when 80% of the group&#8217;s claimed operations in the country were said to have targeted Christian communities.&#160;

See: Analysis: Surge in IS attacks on DR Congo Christians

Source: Telegram messaging service in Arabic 2047 GMT 19 Mar 24

2. Somali President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud the deputy Norwegian foreign affairs minister, Andreas Kravic, &#160;in Mogadishu.&#160; They discussed&#160;bilateral relations as well as social and trade integration. President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud thanked the Norwegian government for extending technical support to the Somali government and humanitarian assistance to destitute people affected by severe drought and seasonal floods that recently destroyed several parts of south-central Somalia.&#160;

3. Government officials, among them, Somali MPs and representatives of the various regional administrations attended celebrations to commemorate International Women&#8217;s Day 2024 in Mogadishu. Somali premier, Hamza Abdi Barre spoke of the role of women in the country&#8217;s pacification processes and fundraising for destitute people affected by floods and security restrictions imposed by terror groups in the country.&#160;

4. Government ministers met in Mogadishu to discuss security, the fight against al-Shabab militant group and stabilization of areas liberated by Somali security forces. Cabinet ministers also approved the nomination of the director-general of Somali Development Bank, Hodan Osman and the assistant director, Adan Roble, urging them to increase the investment portfolio and support micro-finance projects for Somali youths.

5. At least ten people died and many more were injured following an incident of infighting between Somali army commands backed by regional paramilitary forces of Jubbaland state on one side and al-Shabab militant group fighters on the other side near Jamame district, Lower Juba region. The commander of the 5th Battalion of Somalia&#8217;s specially trained commandos known as Danab in Jubbaland state, Major Arab Dheg Ahmed confirmed the destruction of al-Shabab bases and promised to continue security operations to liberate the remaining areas that are under the control of insurgents within the state.&#160;

6. Somali security forces backed by Hirshabelle regional state paramilitary forces and clan vigilantes conducted intensive security operations, clearing explosive materials and destroying al-Shabab militant group bases South of Hiiraan region. The commander of the 5th Brigade of the 27th Division, Col. Mohamed Ibrahim Omar (Bakay) confirmed that the insurgents&#8217; bases had been cleared in several villages including Beryabal, El-Dhere and Nur-Fanah villages north of Bulo-burde districts. The security forces also displayed the bodies of the insurgents who died during the incidents.

7.&#160; Hirshabelle regional state president, Ali Abdulahi Hussein (Ali Gudlawe) held a meeting with regional ministers in the south-central Somali town of Jowhar to discuss security issues, the fight against al-Shabab militant group and coordination of humanitarian assistance for destitute people affected by floods, and climate change impacts. The regional minister for interior and reconciliation, Abdirahman Dahir Gure (Karore) and regional security minister, Mohamed Abdirahman Kheyre reviewed several security issues and ongoing reconciliation efforts to address clan rifts and plans for the second phase of fighting against insurgents and the liberation of the remining areas under their control within the state.&#160;

8. The governor of Mudug region, Abdinasir Abdi Abdulle met commissioners and security officials in the central Somali town of Galkayo to discuss security operations, the fight against al-Shabab militant group and the stabilization of areas liberated by Somali security forces. Town Commissioner Abdirahman Sheikh Hassan Jim&#8217;ale spoke about the cooperation required between security forces and town residents to prevent organised crime, drug dealing, robbery and curtailing the activities of people fuelling clan rifts in the region.&#160;

9. Security forces from the&#160;north-eastern Somali town of Bosaso, the commercial city of Puntland regional state, met the town to discuss security, the fight against al-Shabab and ISIL groups in Bari region. The commander of the regional police force, Col. Abdiqadir Jama Dirir urged security officials to increase their operations to prevent terror attacks from the insurgents.

10. International News Items.

Source: Radio Simba, Mogadishu, in Somali 1000 GMT 7 Mar 24

IS made the claim in a statement issued on behalf its Central Africa Province branch (ISCAP) via its Telegram accounts on 5 March.&#160;

The statement said that on 4 March, IS militants attacked the village of Vemba&#160;in&#160;the Beni region of&#160;North Kivu province.

It claimed that the militants captured and beheaded nine Christians, torched over 10 houses, then returned safely to their positions.&#160;

Civilian Christian villagers have been a key target of ISCAP attacks, with such attacks&#160;markedly increasing in 2023.&#160;These included a previous attack on Vemba last March, in which IS claimed to have killed and captured 10 Christians.&#160;

Source: Telegram messaging service in Arabic 1848 GMT 5 Mar 24
